metadata.name: Industrial Devolution #13
metadata.description:
As the abandoned sewage planet Xnor lay seemingly dormant, aeons crept by. Erosion and oxidation recombined in plumbing, slowly causing the pipes to evolve sentience and grow to the horizon in a blooming chaos of rust, steel and concrete.

Industrial Devolution is the first long-form generative project using my rayhatching algorithm. It combines a raymarcher for SDFs with a surface orientation based flow field renderer in order to draw arbitrary 3D scenes as line art, with an organic, hatched drawing style. The SDF formulas were generatively designed and parametrized to form ancient landscapes of corroded industrial pipes and immense, ageless blocks of concrete.

The entire code of Industrial Devolution is 3930 characters, using no external libraries.

When done rendering, the output can be right-click saved as an SVG file and plotted using a plotter such as an Axidraw. The lines in the SVG are in random order, so it is recommended to use a path reordering/optimizing tool such as axicli or vpype before plotting. This will greatly reduce the plotting time. The output SVG is intended to be plotted at A3 (297x420mm) using a 0.4mm black pen (but feel free to experiment). You can change this by adding these options to the URL:

  &lw=.4 the linewidth in millimetres
  &d=.8 the line density (multiplier to the line width, density 0.6 recommended for plotter output)
  &h=420 how high the page is, in millimetres (width is always height * 0.707)
  &bg=1 set to 0 to remove background rectangle (bg=0 recommended for plotter output)

Industrial Devolution was released during a live minting event at Bright Moments Gallery, Venice Beach in collaboration with Bright Moments, fx(hash) and Tender.

metadata.name: GEN XYZ Das Occult #3760
metadata.description:
A 10k Generative Profile Pic collection
GEN XYZ Das Occult - by culla - @tamccullough

move over cryptopunks
there is a new group on the scene

100% code - not an image composition

A bunch of common palettes
A selection of rare palettes
And a smaller set of ultra rare palettes
However, rarity will be based on what combinations the code produces

The majority of tokens will not have a special trait
However your token might have one or even multiple special traits
But, be aware that only the last special trait added will be listed in the features

Even then, look closely, because not all aspects of the canvas are included in the features. Collectors should still look closely and choose what they like when buying on secondary.

Which team are you on? X or O?

follow culla on twitter for updates. Or maybe __acolyte__

If the non reserved tokens mint out quickly, Access List mints will have 24 hours to mint reserves assigned to those wallets

Thank you for supporting an emerging artist in the generative art space

Access List reserves were given to holders of the following PFP collections created by culla
2x for each Basqunk held
1x for each Inkspunk, TwoFourQunk, V0iD, DeeManz, Punkasso and CR0$$KULL
You would have needed to transfer the above tokens to your mint wallet at the time of the snapshot

metadata.name: WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition #191
metadata.description:
WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition is our official collaboration with Jeres, who was kind enough to work with us in support of the show. The project leans into classic Olympic poster design motifs, embellished by Jeres' signature approach to color and shape. Huge thanks to Jeres for donating their time and enthusiasm to this one, we hope you enjoy it!

As with all WTBS projects, your minting will directly support the podcast and keep us going (and more importantly, collecting!). Our goal is to keep the show free from ads and fully supported by the community, your donations and contributions continue to make that possible. Thank you in advance to everyone who chooses to mint!

Jeres: I love vintage posters. When going to second-hand shops, flea markets or wherever people are selling their used goods, I’m always on the lookout for what people used to hang on their walls. Bauhaus-inspired posters, socialist propaganda, Nagel prints, anything art deco, etc.. but whenever I come across something Olympics inspired I always feel like I hit pay dirt. There’s something about the clean, simple design being used to show people coming together along with the undertones of human excellence that just feels special. And circles. I love circles. I hope you enjoy this collection as much as I enjoyed putting it together with Trinity and Will.

Approximate rarity notes:
5%: Gold Edition
10%: Silver Edition
15%: Bronze Edition 

Commands in fullscreen mode:
S : Save current resolution
1 : Save 2000x3000px
2 : Save 4000x6000px
3 : Save 6000x9000px
4 : Save 8000x12000px
5 : Save 10000x15000px

(The higher the resolution, the longer it takes to render/save. use Chrome for best results.)

metadata.name: 1888 - Levels #9
metadata.description:
Photography: Fede Canovari - Creative-coding: Elout de Kok

Mouse-click switches between:
- screen scaled image
- The large image 
: right-click: save/copy image

A custom created 'soft' pixel 2D/3D engine in vanilla JavaScript
Some info in the source-code; variations on 11 selected photographs.





How can it be, that a photographer from the the Buenos Aires suburbs is working together with like an oldskool creative-coder/artist from the Amsterdam underground?

It's happening in the NFT space - the blockchain. Like a public decentralized hard disk and marketplace all in 1. Hyped, loved and hated; but from the underground and up; all around the world, Artist suddenly are given a platform to directly publish and sell their Art, work together, connect. And are discovering so many other great Artist, fans and collectors. 

It still can be hard, to get noticed; and even sell some of your work.
But then sometimes other Artist and collectors step up, getting moved by the talent and try to high lite these Artist, that also need some love and attention.




Fede Canovari

Hi, my name 's Fede Canovari, born in 93, raised in Florencio Varela, Buenos Aires, Argentina.
I started with photography as a hobby, taking photo with my phone, learning on the internet until with a lot of effort I was able to buy my first camera. 

What I like the most is to take pictures of the things that happen in my neighborhood, I try to reflect the usual, what happens to my neighbors, to my friends and even to me.

It is interesting all the references you find in these images, many things that remind you of the city: a neighbor on the sidewalk, a corner or a group of children riding a bike, what I seek is not to forget what Varela is and where you come from.

Each photograph tells a story, which in turn, reflects a reality that is often overlooked.

Although at first my neighbors did not understand why I took pictures in the streets, I think I was the first one to do it, now they all feel identified with my photos and like to find themselves in them.



Elout de Kok

For the love of Art, and jumping in rain puddles  0__.

I was like 12-13, in the early 80ths and living in the Netherlands, when I first saw the work of graffiti writers on the subways in New York, published in an obscure underground comic magazine. It felt like an alien language, that I still could understand and feel.
And I really loved the sprite-work from videogames; like published by Capcom. Like almost every fast-food place or pub in my town had like a pinball machine and Arcade cabinet, back in the days.

I just thought back then; wow. If I could do that one day...
Then I started to create and work on my own Art, nobody could or would program for me, so I learned to code myself. Do it yourself.

Years later, a great artist-painter I like; told me, when he was 7 years old. He was watching the murals I created back in the 80'ths. That inspired him to pickup Art as well.

I kinda stopped with graffiti in the late 80's. Somehow it all became too crazy-hectic; I felt like a war-veteran with pstd at the age of 19. Gladly, I could move my energy to Art and Coding.
And it's weird, and like with the Internet; I connected and became friends with some of those early oldskool 1970-80's graffiti kings from New York, that I admired as a kid on the other side of the world.

I started to VJ with my computer generated visuals from 1993, it was a way to make some money with generative coding and computer graphics. From crazy underground parties, to flying around the world and vj'n and meeting some heroes of mine like Fatboy Slim, LTJ Bukem, Kraftwerk.


I just hope I can inspire young and old people with my Art and creative coding,
and I just hope they get creative as well. Go! Level-up!  ^__^

July 30, 2022

metadata.name: Gensuzendō #100
metadata.description:
Gensuzendō - Generative Calligraphy
By Frank Force @KilledByAPixel

Hitsuzendō 筆禅道 "way of Zen through brush" is believed by Zen Buddhists to be a method of achieving nirvana. This work is my own way of following that practice.

Features ancient, modern, inverse, and graffiti styles.
Stamps are also generated with many varieties possible.
Right click to save a 2048x2048 image.

Programmed in JavaScript
By Frank Force @KilledByAPixel

Based on my tiny calligraphy generator... https://www.dwitter.net/d/22709

with(x)t?lineWidth=t%5:(scale(9,9),d=Date.now(),fillStyle=R(d%400)),C(a=t+d|stroke())>.9|t>9?beginPath(fillText(String.fromCharCode(d%5e5),129,99)):lineTo(99+4*(z=6*C(t*9*C(a)))*S(a+d),8+t*11+z)

metadata.name: Melody #12
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

The iterations are best viewed in Live Mode.

'Melody' explores color, space and geometry... with a touch of optical illusion thrown in!

It is called 'Melody' because each image resembles notes on a sheet of music.

In live mode:
Click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 1800x2400px PNG.
